    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-08-07T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-08-07T06:00:00-05:00" n="221"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">362.1121 Simpson, Lawrence/208: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-08-07T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 7, 1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received August 7—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>247. Instructions contained in the Department’s telegram 95, July 29, 2 [<hi
                        rend="italic">6</hi>] p.m., carried out.</p>
                <p>The Department’s viewpoint was readily acknowledged at the Foreign Office
                    although as a weak defense it was stated that Simpson himself had requested
                    detention in a concentration camp rather than to be brought before a court of
                    justice. In reply to the report the German Ambassador made after your interview
                    he was informed that serious charges against Simpson involve among other things
                    distribution of Communistic propaganda in Germany for 6 months prior to arrest
                    and that sentence would probably be severe.</p>
                <p>Now that the legal matters reported by the Consulate General yesterday are
                    arranged and after our representations the Foreign Office gave practical
                    assurance that the trial would be set for the forepart of September.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
